DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers Habermas' direct engagements with Max Weber, most
extensively in The Theory of Communicative Action (1981/1984-87), but also
in The Philosophical Discourse of Modernity (1985/1987) and scattered essays.
Habermas' engagement with Weber is not merely scholarly commentary but a
constitutive element of Habermas' own theoretical architecture: he uses Weber
as both a resource and a foil to construct his account of modernity,
rationalization, and the pathologies of modern social life. Three main moves
define Habermas' Weber reception: (1) appropriating Weber's multi-dimensional
concept of rationality while expanding it beyond the purely formal-purposive;
(2) criticizing Weber's "selective" rationalization thesis for reducing
societal rationalization to the institutionalization of purposive-rational
action while neglecting communicative rationalization; (3) repositioning
Weber within the Frankfurt School lineage -- correcting the one-sidedness of
Adorno and Horkheimer's Dialectic of Enlightenment while preserving their
diagnosis of modernity's paradoxes.

The secondary literature on Habermas-Weber falls into three clusters: (a)
commentaries closely following TCA's appropriation of Weber (Ingram, Dahms,
McCarthy); (b) comparisons of Habermas and Weber on specific themes such as
democracy, law, lifeworld, and disenchantment (Breen, Jutten, Hohendahl);
(c) reconstructions of the broader intellectual context, especially Habermas'
relation to the Frankfurt School's Weber reading (Corchia, Bernstein, Honneth
& Joas). A key debate concerns whether Habermas' critique of Weber's
"selective rationalization" is itself one-sided: critics argue that Habermas
imports normative assumptions that Weber deliberately avoided, projecting a
communicative ideal onto a contested historical account.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is the most directly relevant to the research project: it
identifies the precise textual locations where Habermas engages Weber and
reconstructs the theoretical purposes driving those engagements. The
secondary literature helps assess the adequacy of Habermas' reading and
situates it within broader debates about modernity, rationalization, and
the scope of critical theory. Central to the project's concern with
history, development, and methodology is Habermas' claim that Weber's own
theory, properly reconstructed, points beyond Weber's pessimistic
"diagnosis of the times."

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The search returned fewer English-language journal articles directly focused
on Habermas' methodology vis-a-vis Weber's Verstehen sociology than expected;
this dimension is largely treated as internal to book-length studies.
Several Russian-language translations of TCA sections on Weber appear in
databases but lack independent scholarly significance for this domain.
The recent (post-2010) literature tends toward specialized sub-questions
(law, democracy, neoliberalism) rather than comprehensive accounts of
Habermas' Weber reception.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should distinguish between Habermas as interpreter of Weber
(in TCA) and Habermas as theorist who departs from Weber (in PDM and later
work). The colonization thesis (TCA Vol 2) and the disenchantment analysis
(TCA Vol 1) should be treated as connected moments within a single
argumentative strategy. Schluchter's "Rise of Western Rationalism" provides
a useful independent reconstruction of Weber that can serve as a touchstone
for evaluating Habermas' reading.

